  "prompt": "What are the best TED Talks by youth?",
  "response": "TED Talks have featured many young speakers who have delivered compelling and inspiring talks. While \"best\" can be subjective, here are some highly regarded TED Talks by youth:\n\n1. **Adora Svitak**: \"What Adults Can Learn from Kids\"\n   - Adora, a child prodigy and author, argues that the world needs \"childish\" thinking: bold ideas, wild creativity, and optimism.\n\n2. **Thomas Suarez**: \"A 12-Year-Old App Developer\"\n   - Thomas shares his journey of developing apps and the importance of encouraging kids to explore technology.\n\n3. **Taylor Wilson**: \"My Radical Plan for Small Nuclear Fission Reactors\" \n   - Taylor, a young nuclear physicist, talks about how he built a nuclear fusion reactor and his plans for safer, smaller nuclear fission reactors.\n\n4. **Tavi Gevinson**: \"A Teen Just Trying to Figure it Out\"\n   - Tavi, a fashion blogger and editor, discusses her experiences and the need for authentic teen voices in media.\n\n5. **Logan LaPlante**: \"Hackschooling Makes Me Happy\"\n   - Logan talks about how he \"hacks\" his education to include more real-world experiences and creative pursuits, promoting happiness.\n\n6. **Sparsh Shah**: \"How a 13-year-old Changed 'Impossible' to 'I'm possible'\"\n   - Sparsh, a young musician with brittle bone disease, shares his inspiring story of overcoming challenges and pursuing his passion for music.\n\n7. **Greta Thunberg**: \"The Disarming Case to Act Right Now on Climate Change\"\n   - Greta, the young climate activist, speaks about the urgency of addressing climate change and her journey in activism.\n\n8. **Shubham Banerjee**: \"A 13-Year-Old's Quest for a Low-Cost Braille Printer\"\n   - Shubham discusses how he created a Braille printer using LEGO, aiming to make technology more accessible to the visually impaired.\n\nThese talks showcase the incredible talents and perspectives of young individuals, offering valuable insights and inspiration across various fields, from technology to activism to education.",
